What is swap and when is it used? - Yes — much slower than RAM, because it's on disk.
Using swap excessively leads to high disk I/O and slow performance — this is called swapping. Swap is a type of disk space that your Linux system uses as virtual memory when RAM is full.
Situation	              What Happens
RAM is sufficient	    Swap is not used
RAM is getting full 	Linux starts to use swap for less-used pages
RAM is completely used	Swap prevents crashes (but slows down system)
free -h

Where would look to find system logs? --cat /var/log/syslog

How can I see all processes that are running? How about which ones are taking up the most CPU/Memory? ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head -n 10 OR ps aux --sort=-%mem | head -n 10 or TOP(Press c or M)

How do you restart a service? systemctl

How do you see what IP address is assigned to the box? - ip a OR ifconfig

How do you install a package for both RHEL and Ubuntu/Debian? - sudo apt update ; sudo apt install

What is /etc/fstab used for? --/etc/fstab (file system table) is a configuration file in Linux that defines how and what filesystems should be mounted automatically at boot time.

